  "notes": "Old Frisian (~1150–1550 CE). The earliest attested Frisian, known primarily from legal manuscripts (the Rüstring, Hunsingoer, Emsiger, and Brokmer law codes). Ancestor of all modern Frisian languages (West, North, Saterland). KEY FEATURES: (1) ANGLO-FRISIAN BRIGHTENING: PGmc *a → ā/ē before nasals (shared with Old English but not Old Saxon/OHG). (2) INGVAEONIC NASAL SPIRANT LAW: nasal lost before fricative with compensatory lengthening — *munþ → mūth, *fimf → fīf (shared with OE, OS). (3) PALATALISATION: PGmc *k → ts/tz before front vowels — *kinn → tsieze 'cheese', distinct from OE tʃ and absent in OS. (4) NO HIGH GERMAN CONSONANT SHIFT. (5) Retained þ/ð until late period. (6) Geminate consonants still distinctive. Most closely related to Old English; together they form the Anglo-Frisian sub-branch. Sources: Bremmer (2009), Stiles (1995), Markey (1981).",
